Note: ================================================================
Note: Bifrost Formal Verification
Note: ================================================================
Note: Formal verification for memory safety, data-race freedom, and
Note: resource bounds in Bifrost graphs. Provides static guarantees
Note: about accelerator kernel correctness and safety.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/graph.runa" as Graph
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/node.runa" as Node
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/edge.runa" as Edge
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as String
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Math

Note: ================================================================
Note: Verification Result Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant VERIFY_PASS as Integer is 0
Constant VERIFY_FAIL as Integer is 1
Constant VERIFY_UNKNOWN as Integer is 2

Note: ================================================================
Note: Safety Violation Types
Note: ================================================================

Constant VIOLATION_NONE as Integer is 0
Constant VIOLATION_BUFFER_OVERFLOW as Integer is 1
Constant VIOLATION_NULL_DEREF as Integer is 2
Constant VIOLATION_DATA_RACE as Integer is 3
Constant VIOLATION_DEADLOCK as Integer is 4
Constant VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED as Integer is 5
Constant VIOLATION_UNINITIALIZED_READ as Integer is 6
Constant VIOLATION_INVALID_ALIGNMENT as Integer is 7

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
VerificationResult is the uniform return type for every verifier entry point. It carries the verdict (status: PASS/FAIL/UNKNOWN), the specific safety category that was violated (violation_type), the node where the violation was detected (violation_location), and a human-readable error string. All five top-level verifier procs return this type so verify_graph can chain checks and surface the first failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24. Status and violation_type are read by orchestrator code via memory_get_int64. violation_location is a node pointer (0 when status == PASS). error_message is a String that downstream diagnostics formatters consume.
@End Implementation

Type called "VerificationResult":
    status as Integer               Note: VERIFY_PASS, VERIFY_FAIL, VERIFY_UNKNOWN
    violation_type as Integer       Note: VIOLATION_* constant
    violation_location as Integer   Note: Pointer to node where violation occurs
    error_message as String         Note: Human-readable error description
End Type

@Reasoning:
MemorySafetyProof decomposes the memory safety verdict into its three sub-properties: bounds-checked, null-deref-free, alignment-verified. Carrying these flags separately lets the verifier produce diagnostics that pinpoint which aspect of memory safety failed instead of returning a single opaque boolean.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24. Each field is Boolean (Integer at runtime). The overall is_safe is the AND of the three sub-flags; the verifier sets the relevant flag to false and is_safe to false on first failure.
@End Implementation

Type called "MemorySafetyProof":
    is_safe as Boolean              Note: Whether memory safety is proven
    buffer_bounds_verified as Boolean Note: All accesses within bounds
    no_null_derefs as Boolean       Note: No null pointer dereferences
    alignment_verified as Boolean   Note: All accesses properly aligned
End Type

@Reasoning:
RaceFreedomProof captures the result of data-race-freedom verification. is_race_free is the verdict; happens_before_graph is the pointer to the transitive-closure graph used to decide concurrency; conflicting_accesses is the list of access pairs that needed synchronization checking; synchronization_verified indicates whether all conflicts were resolved by valid happens-before edges.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24. happens_before_graph and conflicting_accesses are pointers (Integer offsets to allocated Lists/graph structures). is_race_free and synchronization_verified are Booleans.
@End Implementation

Type called "RaceFreedomProof":
    is_race_free as Boolean         Note: Whether data-race freedom is proven
    happens_before_graph as Integer Note: Pointer to happens-before relation
    conflicting_accesses as Integer Note: List of potential race pairs
    synchronization_verified as Boolean Note: Proper synchronization present
End Type

@Reasoning:
ResourceBounds carries both the hardware limits and the actual measured usage for the three resource axes Bifrost tracks (memory bytes, registers per thread, threads per block) plus a final within_limits verdict. verify_resource_bounds populates this struct and within_limits is true iff every actual_* is within the corresponding *_limit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40/48. Reading limits at offsets 0/8/16 and actuals at 24/32/40 matches the comparison loop in verify_resource_bounds. within_limits at offset 48 is the AND of the three per-axis comparisons.
@End Implementation

Type called "ResourceBounds":
    memory_limit as Integer         Note: Maximum memory usage in bytes
    register_limit as Integer       Note: Maximum registers per thread
    thread_limit as Integer         Note: Maximum threads per block
    actual_memory as Integer        Note: Actual memory usage
    actual_registers as Integer     Note: Actual register usage
    actual_threads as Integer       Note: Actual thread count
    within_limits as Boolean        Note: Whether all limits satisfied
End Type

@Reasoning:
HappensBeforeRelation records the temporal ordering between two nodes: 0 = concurrent (no ordering), 1 = node1 before node2, 2 = node2 before node1. Used by query_happens_before as the return-value encoding so callers can branch on the three possible relations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-slot record at offsets 0/8/16. relation_type uses the integer encoding {0,1,2}; query_happens_before reads it via memory_get_int64 from offset 16.
@End Implementation

Type called "HappensBeforeRelation":
    node1 as Integer                Note: First node
    node2 as Integer                Note: Second node
    relation_type as Integer        Note: 0=concurrent, 1=before, 2=after
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Memory Safety Verification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level memory safety verifier. Three properties guarantee memory safety for Bifrost graphs: buffer accesses within bounds (no buffer overflow), pointer non-nullness (no null dereferences), and address alignment (matches element size). Returns the first violation encountered rather than the full list because callers (typically verify_graph) want the earliest actionable diagnostic, not an exhaustive enumeration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. extract_memory_operations(all_nodes) filters to Load (OpKind 40) and Store (OpKind 41).
2. For each memory op, run verify_buffer_bounds, verify_non_null_pointer, verify_alignment in that order.
3. On first failure, populate result.status = VERIFY_FAIL, set the corresponding VIOLATION_* code, record the violating node, write a descriptive error_message, and return immediately.
4. If all checks pass, set "Memory safety verified" and return PASS.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(M * (B + N + A)) where M is memory op count and B/N/A are per-op bounds/null/alignment costs. Bounds and alignment dominate due to recursive range/alignment analysis on the address subgraph.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Top-level safety check. Read-only on graph. The early-exit-on-first-violation policy means subsequent unsafe ops are not reported in a single pass; orchestrators that need exhaustive reporting can call this in a loop after fixing each.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_memory_safety" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be a value of type VerificationResult with
        status as VERIFY_PASS,
        violation_type as VIOLATION_NONE,
        violation_location as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Get all nodes
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph

    Note: Extract memory operations
    Let memory_ops be extract_memory_operations(all_nodes)
    Let op_count be proc length from List with memory_ops

    Note: Verify each memory operation
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than op_count:
        Let mem_op be proc get from List with memory_ops, i

        Note: Verify buffer bounds
        Let bounds_safe be verify_buffer_bounds(graph, mem_op)
        If bounds_safe is equal to false:
            Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
            Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_BUFFER_OVERFLOW
            Set result.violation_location to mem_op
            Set result.error_message to "Buffer overflow detected"
            Return result
        End If

        Note: Verify non-null pointer
        Let pointer_valid be verify_non_null_pointer(graph, mem_op)
        If pointer_valid is equal to false:
            Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
            Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_NULL_DEREF
            Set result.violation_location to mem_op
            Set result.error_message to "Null pointer dereference detected"
            Return result
        End If

        Note: Verify alignment
        Let alignment_ok be verify_alignment(graph, mem_op)
        If alignment_ok is equal to false:
            Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
            Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_INVALID_ALIGNMENT
            Set result.violation_location to mem_op
            Set result.error_message to "Invalid memory alignment"
            Return result
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: All checks passed
    Set result.error_message to "Memory safety verified"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Buffer-bounds verifier for a single memory op. Proves 0 <= min_index AND max_index < buffer_size using range analysis on the index expression and buffer-size extraction from the allocation/declaration. Returns false (cannot prove safe) when either bound is violated or the analysis lacks information; this conservative answer preserves soundness at the cost of false positives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. inputs = get_node_inputs(mem_op); bail false if empty (malformed op).
2. address_node = first input.
3. extract_base_index decomposes the address into (base_ptr, index_node).
4. get_buffer_size(graph, base_ptr) returns the upper bound (in bytes or elements depending on the allocation - currently bytes).
5. compute_value_range(index_node) returns [min, max].
6. Return false if min < 0 OR max >= buffer_size; true otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by recursive compute_value_range over the index expression DAG and the buffer-size trace back to allocation. Typically O(depth_of_index_DAG + depth_of_allocation_chain).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only on graph. No mutation. Returns false on inconclusive analysis to preserve soundness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_buffer_bounds" that takes graph as Integer, mem_op as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Get address computation (first input)
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with mem_op
    If proc length from List with inputs is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let address_node be proc get from List with inputs, 0

    Note: Extract base and index from address computation
    Let addr_info be extract_base_index(graph, address_node)
    Let base_ptr be proc get from List with addr_info, 0
    Let index_node be proc get from List with addr_info, 1

    Note: Get buffer size from base pointer
    Let buffer_size be get_buffer_size(graph, base_ptr)

    Note: Perform range analysis on index
    Let index_range be compute_value_range(graph, index_node)
    Let min_index be proc get from List with index_range, 0
    Let max_index be proc get from List with index_range, 1

    Note: Verify: 0 <= min_index AND max_index < buffer_size
    If min_index is less than 0:
        Return false
    End If

    If max_index is greater than or equal to buffer_size:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-dereference verifier for a single memory op. Bifrost has two ABI-guaranteed non-null sources: Input nodes (kernel parameters - non-null by calling convention) and direct Alloc nodes (OpKind 42 - returns a fresh non-null pointer or fails before reaching the load/store). Other pointer origins are conservatively assumed nullable and return false.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Get address_node from mem_op's first input.
2. Check is_input via get_node_type comparison with NodeType.Input (1); return true if input.
3. Walk address_node's predecessors looking for an Alloc op (OpKind 42); return true on match.
4. No match -> return false (conservative).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(predecessors of address_node). Could be improved with caching across multiple mem_ops sharing the same address.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only graph analysis. Conservative false on inconclusive cases preserves soundness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_non_null_pointer" that takes graph as Integer, mem_op as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Get address computation
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with mem_op
    If proc length from List with inputs is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let address_node be proc get from List with inputs, 0

    Note: Check if address is from allocation or input parameter
    Let is_input be proc get_node_type from Node with address_node is equal to 1

    Note: Input parameters are assumed non-null (calling convention)
    If is_input is equal to true:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check if from allocation node
    Let predecessors be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with graph, address_node

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than proc length from List with predecessors:
        Let pred be proc get from List with predecessors, i
        Let pred_op be proc get_node_opkind from Node with pred

        Note: Alloc operation guarantees non-null (or fails)
        If pred_op is equal to 42:
            Return true
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Conservative: cannot prove non-null
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Alignment verifier for a memory op. Proves the address is aligned to a multiple of the element size. Most modern ISAs trap on misaligned vectorized loads/stores, so misalignment is a correctness bug not just a performance issue. Requires element_size to be a power of 2 (otherwise alignment cannot be expressed as a bit mask).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. element_size = byte size of mem_op's output type via get_type_size_bytes.
2. is_power_of_two(element_size); return false on non-power-of-2.
3. address_node = first input.
4. computed_alignment = compute_alignment(graph, address_node) which propagates alignment through arithmetic ops.
5. Return true if computed_alignment >= element_size, or if element_size is a multiple of computed_alignment (compatible alignment).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Returns false on inconclusive cases (e.g. non-power-of-2 element size).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_alignment" that takes graph as Integer, mem_op as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Get element size
    Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with mem_op
    Let element_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with output_type

    Note: Element size must be power-of-2 for alignment
    Let is_pow2 be is_power_of_two(element_size)
    If is_pow2 is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Get address computation
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with mem_op
    If proc length from List with inputs is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let address_node be proc get from List with inputs, 0

    Note: Track alignment through address computation
    Let computed_alignment be compute_alignment(graph, address_node)

    Note: Check if alignment is sufficient
    If computed_alignment is greater than or equal to element_size:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check if alignment is compatible (element_size % alignment == 0)
    If element_size modulo by computed_alignment is equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Data Race Freedom Verification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level data-race-freedom verifier. A data race exists when two memory accesses to the same location with at least one write are not ordered by a happens-before relation. The algorithm builds the happens-before graph from synchronization edges, then checks every pair of memory ops for the (conflict, write, no-HB) signature.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. build_happens_before_graph computes the HB closure of the IR.
2. extract_memory_operations gives the Load/Store node list.
3. Double loop over pairs (i, j) where j > i to avoid double-checking.
4. check_memory_conflict(op1, op2) tests aliasing.
5. has_write_operation(op1, op2) tests that at least one is a Store.
6. query_happens_before returns 0 (concurrent) on no-HB; concurrent + conflict + write -> race; set VIOLATION_DATA_RACE and return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(M^2) for the pair loop plus O(N + E) for happens-before graph construction. Could be O(M log M) with an alias-class bucketing optimization on check_memory_conflict.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Conservative reporting on first race. The happens-before graph is allocated and held for the duration of the check.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_data_race_freedom" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be a value of type VerificationResult with
        status as VERIFY_PASS,
        violation_type as VIOLATION_NONE,
        violation_location as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Build happens-before graph
    Let hb_graph be build_happens_before_graph(graph)

    Note: Get all memory operations
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let memory_ops be extract_memory_operations(all_nodes)
    Let op_count be proc length from List with memory_ops

    Note: Check all pairs for races
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than op_count:
        Let op1 be proc get from List with memory_ops, i

        Let j be i plus 1
        While j is less than op_count:
            Let op2 be proc get from List with memory_ops, j

            Note: Check if operations conflict (same address)
            Let conflict be check_memory_conflict(op1, op2)

            If conflict is greater than 0:
                Note: Check if at least one is write
                Let has_write be has_write_operation(op1, op2)

                If has_write is equal to true:
                    Note: Check happens-before relation
                    Let hb_relation be query_happens_before(hb_graph, op1, op2)

                    Note: If no happens-before (concurrent), race exists
                    If hb_relation is equal to 0:
                        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
                        Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_DATA_RACE
                        Set result.violation_location to op1
                        Set result.error_message to "Data race detected between operations"
                        Return result
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result.error_message to "Data race freedom verified"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs the happens-before relation as a directed graph. An edge A->B in the HB graph means "A must complete before B starts." HB is induced by program-order within a thread, synchronization operations (barriers, fences, atomics), and transitivity. Bifrost encodes synchronization as Control edges (EdgeKind 1) in the data flow graph, so HB construction extracts those edges and takes their transitive closure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. create_graph allocates a fresh graph for HB.
2. Copy every node from the original via add_node (HB graph has the same vertex set).
3. Iterate every edge; if its kind == 1 (Control / EdgeKind.Control), add the same directed edge to the HB graph.
4. compute_transitive_closure on the HB graph; the closure is what query_happens_before consults.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E) for the initial graph + Floyd-Warshall-style O(N^3) for the transitive closure inside compute_transitive_closure. For Bifrost graphs (typically dozens to low hundreds of nodes) this is acceptable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Allocates a new graph owned by the caller. Reads original graph topology.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_happens_before_graph" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create happens-before graph
    Let hb_graph be proc create_graph from Graph

    Note: Get all nodes and add to hb graph
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i
        proc add_node from Graph with hb_graph, node
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add control edges as happens-before edges
    Let all_edges be proc get_all_edges from Graph with graph
    Let edge_count be proc length from List with all_edges

    Let j be 0
    While j is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be proc get from List with all_edges, j
        Let edge_kind be proc get_edge_kind from Edge with edge

        Note: Control edge = happens-before
        If edge_kind is equal to 1:
            Let source be proc get_edge_source from Edge with edge
            Let dest be proc get_edge_dest from Edge with edge
            proc add_edge from Graph with hb_graph, source, dest, edge_kind, 0
        End If

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute transitive closure for full happens-before relation
    Let hb_closure be proc compute_transitive_closure from Graph with hb_graph

    Return hb_closure
End Process

@Reasoning:
Queries the precomputed happens-before graph for the relation between two ops. Returns one of three encodings: 0 (concurrent - no HB edge in either direction, meaning the ops can race), 1 (op1 -> op2 - op1 happens before op2), 2 (op2 -> op1 - op2 happens before op1). The encoding matches the HappensBeforeRelation type's relation_type field.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. has_edge(hb_graph, op1, op2): if true, return 1.
2. has_edge(hb_graph, op2, op1): if true, return 2.
3. Otherwise return 0 (concurrent).
@End Implementation

Process called "query_happens_before" that takes hb_graph as Integer, op1 as Integer, op2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if op1 happens-before op2
    Let has_edge_1_to_2 be proc has_edge from Graph with hb_graph, op1, op2
    If has_edge_1_to_2 is equal to true:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check if op2 happens-before op1
    Let has_edge_2_to_1 be proc has_edge from Graph with hb_graph, op2, op1
    If has_edge_2_to_1 is equal to true:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Concurrent (no happens-before)
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Resource Bounds Verification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the kernel stays within hardware resource budgets for memory, registers, and threads. The three axes are independent: a kernel can fit in registers and threads but exceed memory, or vice versa. Returns VERIFY_FAIL with VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED and an axis-specific error message on the first violation, allowing the user to know which budget needs trimming.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read three limits from the limits struct at offsets 0/8/16 (memory, register, thread).
2. compute_memory_usage, compute_register_usage, compute_thread_count on the graph.
3. Sequential gates: memory then registers then threads. First violation populates VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED with the specific message ("Memory limit exceeded", "Register limit exceeded", "Thread limit exceeded") and returns.
4. All-pass: set "Resource bounds verified" and return PASS.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by compute_memory_usage (O(N)), compute_register_usage (O(N) liveness pass), and compute_thread_count (O(N)). Single graph traversal each.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Allocates a fresh VerificationResult.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_resource_bounds" that takes graph as Integer, limits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be a value of type VerificationResult with
        status as VERIFY_PASS,
        violation_type as VIOLATION_NONE,
        violation_location as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Extract limits
    Let memory_limit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with limits, 0
    Let register_limit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with limits, 8
    Let thread_limit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with limits, 16

    Note: Compute actual usage
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let actual_memory be compute_memory_usage(graph, all_nodes)
    Let actual_registers be compute_register_usage(graph, all_nodes)
    Let actual_threads be compute_thread_count(graph)

    Note: Check memory limit
    If actual_memory is greater than memory_limit:
        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
        Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED
        Set result.error_message to "Memory limit exceeded"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Check register limit
    If actual_registers is greater than register_limit:
        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
        Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED
        Set result.error_message to "Register limit exceeded"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Check thread limit
    If actual_threads is greater than thread_limit:
        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
        Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_RESOURCE_EXCEEDED
        Set result.error_message to "Thread limit exceeded"
        Return result
    End If

    Set result.error_message to "Resource bounds verified"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sums the bytes-resident-in-memory across every node in the graph. Each node contributes its output type's byte size; this is the conservative upper bound assuming no liveness-based memory reuse (every value lives forever). The number feeds verify_resource_bounds's memory-limit comparison.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Initialize total_memory = 0.
2. For each node, get_node_output_type and read its byte size via get_type_size_bytes.
3. Accumulate.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_memory_usage" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total_memory be 0

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i

        Note: Get output type size
        Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
        Let type_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with output_type

        Note: Add to total
        Set total_memory to total_memory plus type_size

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return total_memory
End Process

@Reasoning:
Computes peak register pressure as max_simultaneous_live_values plus a 20% overhead margin for compiler temporaries. compute_liveness returns the SSA-liveness peak directly; the overhead accounts for spill temporaries, address calculation temporaries, and inlined intrinsics that the register allocator needs but liveness misses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. compute_liveness(graph, nodes) returns a list whose first element is max_live.
2. overhead = max_live / 5 (20% margin).
3. Return max_live + overhead.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_register_usage" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform liveness analysis
    Let liveness be compute_liveness(graph, nodes)
    Let max_live be proc get from List with liveness, 0

    Note: Add overhead for compiler temporaries (20% margin)
    Let overhead be max_live divided by 5
    Let total_registers be max_live plus overhead

    Return total_registers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Estimates the maximum thread count the kernel needs. For data-parallel ops (parallelism kind 1 = DataParallel), the thread count is the cardinality of the output's iteration space (vector size, matrix elements, or tensor shape product). Returns the max across all data-parallel ops because that determines the block dimension the launcher must request.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Initialize max_threads = 1 (minimum sensible thread count).
2. For each node, get_node_parallelism; only process nodes with parallelism == 1 (DataParallel).
3. compute_data_parallel_threads on the node's output type returns the element count.
4. Update max_threads on any node that exceeds it.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_thread_count" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find all nodes
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Let max_threads be 1

    Note: Find maximum parallelism degree
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i

        Note: Get parallelism model
        Let parallelism be proc get_node_parallelism from Node with node

        Note: For data-parallel, get data size
        If parallelism is equal to 1:
            Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
            Let thread_count be compute_data_parallel_threads(output_type)

            If thread_count is greater than max_threads:
                Set max_threads to thread_count
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return max_threads
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Termination Verification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Termination verifier. Pure DAGs trivially terminate (no loops -> finite execution). If the graph has cycles (allowed in Bifrost for software-pipelined loops with explicit back-edges), verify_loop_bounds checks each cycle for an external bound. An unbounded loop returns VERIFY_FAIL.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. is_dag(graph): if true, return PASS with "Termination verified (DAG)".
2. find_cycle returns one cycle path. If non-zero, run verify_loop_bounds on it.
3. verify_loop_bounds returning false sets VERIFY_FAIL with "Unbounded loop detected".
4. Bounded cycle returns PASS with "Termination verified (bounded loops)".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Conservative: any inconclusive case returns FAIL.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_termination" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be a value of type VerificationResult with
        status as VERIFY_PASS,
        violation_type as VIOLATION_NONE,
        violation_location as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Check if graph is DAG
    Let is_dag be proc is_dag from Graph with graph

    If is_dag is equal to true:
        Set result.error_message to "Termination verified (DAG)"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Graph has cycles - check loop bounds
    Let cycles be proc find_cycle from Graph with graph

    If cycles is not equal to 0:
        Note: Analyze loop bounds
        Let bounded be verify_loop_bounds(graph, cycles)

        If bounded is equal to false:
            Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
            Set result.error_message to "Unbounded loop detected"
            Return result
        End If
    End If

    Set result.error_message to "Termination verified (bounded loops)"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Structural test: every node in a cycle must have at least one predecessor that originates outside the cycle and is either Constant (NodeType 0) or Input (NodeType 1). The principle is that loop iteration counts are determined by external bounds; any cycle whose only predecessors are also in the cycle has no upper bound and may iterate forever.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build loop_member Dict from the loop_nodes list.
2. For each node n in the loop, get its predecessors.
3. For each predecessor not in loop_member, check NodeType: if 0 (Constant) or 1 (Input), set has_external_bound = true.
4. If any loop node has no external-bound predecessor, return false.
5. All loop nodes have external bounds -> return true.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L * P) where L is loop_nodes count and P is average predecessor count. Linear in loop size.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only graph analysis. Conservative false on any inconclusive case preserves soundness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_loop_bounds" that takes graph as Integer, loop_nodes as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: A loop is bounded iff every node participating in the cycle has
    Note: at least one Constant operand (the upper bound) and at least one
    Note: induction-variable-style chain that monotonically converges. We
    Note: verify this structurally: every node in the loop must have a
    Note: predecessor outside the loop that is either Constant or Input
    Note: (a kernel parameter, which is treated as a bound by ABI).
    Let loop_size be proc length from List with loop_nodes
    If loop_size is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let loop_member be proc create from Dict
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than loop_size:
        Let mn be proc get from List with loop_nodes, m
        proc set from Dict with loop_member, mn, 1
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than loop_size:
        Let n be proc get from List with loop_nodes, i
        Let preds be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with 0, n
        Let pc be proc length from List with preds
        Let has_external_bound be false
        Let p be 0
        While p is less than pc:
            Let pred be proc get from List with preds, p
            Let in_loop be proc get from Dict with loop_member, pred
            If in_loop is equal to 0:
                Let pred_type be proc get_node_type from Node with pred
                If pred_type is equal to 0:
                    Set has_external_bound to true
                End If
                If pred_type is equal to 1:
                    Set has_external_bound to true
                End If
            End If
            Set p to p plus 1
        End While
        If has_external_bound is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Synchronization Validation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two-gate synchronization validator. Gate 1 (barrier alignment): every thread in a warp/block must reach each barrier under identical control conditions; a Branch op before a barrier that gates some threads out is a hazard. Gate 2 (deadlock): the happens-before graph must be acyclic; a cycle means thread A waits for thread B which waits for A.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. extract_sync_operations filters to OpKinds 60..69 (barriers, atomics, fences).
2. verify_barrier_alignment scans for divergent control predecessors before each barrier.
3. check_deadlock builds the HB graph and tests for cycles.
4. First failure populates VIOLATION_DEADLOCK or barrier-misalignment message; PASS otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Allocates the HB graph internally inside check_deadlock.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_synchronization" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be a value of type VerificationResult with
        status as VERIFY_PASS,
        violation_type as VIOLATION_NONE,
        violation_location as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Find synchronization operations
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let sync_ops be extract_sync_operations(all_nodes)

    Note: Verify barrier alignment
    Let barriers_aligned be verify_barrier_alignment(graph, sync_ops)

    If barriers_aligned is equal to false:
        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
        Set result.error_message to "Barrier misalignment detected"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Check for deadlocks
    Let has_deadlock be check_deadlock(graph, sync_ops)

    If has_deadlock is equal to true:
        Set result.status to VERIFY_FAIL
        Set result.violation_type to VIOLATION_DEADLOCK
        Set result.error_message to "Potential deadlock detected"
        Return result
    End If

    Set result.error_message to "Synchronization validated"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies every barrier is reached by all threads under the same control conditions. The hazard is a conditional Branch (OpKind 36) immediately before a barrier where the false-branch escapes elsewhere; threads taking the escape path skip the barrier, leaving the remaining threads waiting forever (deadlock).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. For each barrier in the list, get its predecessors.
2. For each predecessor whose OpKind == 36 (Branch), examine the Branch's successors.
3. If the Branch has more than one successor AND any successor != this barrier, set other_target = true and return false (divergent control before barrier).
4. All barriers pass alignment check -> return true.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Read-only graph analysis.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_barrier_alignment" that takes graph as Integer, barriers as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: A barrier is "aligned" iff every thread in the warp/block reaches
    Note: it under the same control conditions. Structurally, a barrier
    Note: node B is aligned iff every predecessor path from the kernel
    Note: entry to B has no conditional Branch (OpKind 36) that gates B
    Note: differently for different threads. We verify by checking that
    Note: each barrier's predecessor set has no Branch node whose other
    Note: successor escapes back to a non-barrier control point.
    Let barrier_count be proc length from List with barriers
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than barrier_count:
        Let barrier be proc get from List with barriers, i
        Let preds be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with graph, barrier
        Let pc be proc length from List with preds
        Let p be 0
        While p is less than pc:
            Let pred be proc get from List with preds, p
            Let pred_op be proc get_node_opkind from Node with pred
            Note: Conditional Branch (OpKind 36) before a barrier creates
            Note: divergence iff some thread doesn't reach this barrier.
            If pred_op is equal to 36:
                Let pred_succs be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, pred
                Let psc be proc length from List with pred_succs
                If psc is greater than 1:
                    Note: Branch with multiple successors and at least one
                    Note: of them isn't this barrier -> divergent control.
                    Let s be 0
                    Let other_target be false
                    While s is less than psc:
                        Let succ be proc get from List with pred_succs, s
                        If succ is not equal to barrier:
                            Set other_target to true
                        End If
                        Set s to s plus 1
                    End While
                    If other_target is equal to true:
                        Return false
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set p to p plus 1
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deadlock detector via cycle-finding on the happens-before graph. A circular wait (A waits for B which waits for A) manifests as a cycle in HB. Pure DAG synchronization is provably deadlock-free; any cycle is at minimum a deadlock hazard.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. build_happens_before_graph produces the HB closure.
2. has_cycle(hb_graph) returns the boolean verdict.
3. Returns true if a cycle is found (potential deadlock).
@End Implementation

Process called "check_deadlock" that takes graph as Integer, sync_ops as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if synchronization creates cycles
    Note: Use happens-before graph
    Let hb_graph be build_happens_before_graph(graph)

    Note: Check for cycles
    Let has_cycle be proc has_cycle from Graph with hb_graph

    Return has_cycle
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Verification Orchestration
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level verification driver. Chains the five orthogonal verifier passes in dependency order: memory safety first (cheapest, most common failure mode), then race freedom (needs HB graph), then resource bounds (needs liveness analysis), then termination (needs cycle detection), then synchronization (needs HB graph again). Returns the first failure verbatim so callers get the most actionable diagnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. verify_memory_safety; read status at offset 0; bail out on != PASS.
2. verify_data_race_freedom; same pattern.
3. verify_resource_bounds(graph, resource_limits).
4. verify_termination.
5. validate_synchronization.
6. All pass: allocate a fresh VerificationResult with PASS, "All verification checks passed".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Worst-case sum of all five sub-passes: roughly O(N^2 + M^2 + E*log(N)) where N is node count, M is memory op count, E is edge count. The pair-loop in race detection is dominant.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Top-level read-only orchestrator. Allocates verification results internally; no graph mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verify_graph" that takes graph as Integer, resource_limits as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Memory safety
    Let safety_result be verify_memory_safety(graph)
    Let safety_status be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with safety_result, 0

    If safety_status is not equal to VERIFY_PASS:
        Return safety_result
    End If

    Note: Data race freedom
    Let race_result be verify_data_race_freedom(graph)
    Let race_status be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with race_result, 0

    If race_status is not equal to VERIFY_PASS:
        Return race_result
    End If

    Note: Resource bounds
    Let resource_result be verify_resource_bounds(graph, resource_limits)
    Let resource_status be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with resource_result, 0

    If resource_status is not equal to VERIFY_PASS:
        Return resource_result
    End If

    Note: Termination
    Let term_result be verify_termination(graph)
    Let term_status be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with term_result, 0

    If term_status is not equal to VERIFY_PASS:
        Return term_result
    End If

    Note: Synchronization
    Let sync_result be validate_synchronization(graph)
    Let sync_status be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with sync_result, 0

    If sync_status is not equal to VERIFY_PASS:
        Return sync_result
    End If

    Note: All verifications passed
Let final_result be a value of type VerificationResult    Set final_result.status to VERIFY_PASS    Set final_result.violation_type to VIOLATION_NONE    Set final_result.violation_location to 0    Set final_result.error_message to "All verification checks passed"    Return final_result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Range Analysis
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes the static value range [min, max] for a node. Constants have a singleton range; arithmetic ops (Add, Sub, Mul) propagate their operand ranges via interval arithmetic. The range narrows the possible index values for buffer-bounds checking. For nodes whose value cannot be bounded statically, returns the conservative [0, 1000000] interval.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. is_node_constant: if true, read constant payload at offset 8 and return [v, v].
2. Otherwise read op_kind and inputs.
3. For binary arithmetic (2 inputs): recursively compute_value_range on each.
4. Add (op 0): [l_min+r_min, l_max+r_max].
5. Subtract (op 1): [l_min-r_max, l_max-r_min].
6. Multiply (op 2, both non-negative): [l_min*r_min, l_max*r_max].
7. Fallback: return [0, 1000000] as conservative range.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Worst case O(N) for the recursive descent over the expression DAG. Memoization would reduce repeated subtree work but is not currently applied.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only graph analysis. Conservative range on unmodeled ops preserves soundness for bounds checking.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_value_range" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if constant. For constants, we know the value precisely.
    Let is_constant be proc is_node_constant from Node with node

    If is_constant is equal to true:
        Note: Constant payload value is stored at offset 8 of the node
        Note: descriptor (Constant payload follows the discriminant).
        Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
        Let range be proc create from List
        proc append from List with range, v
        proc append from List with range, v
        Return range
    End If

    Note: For non-constants, recursively compute by op kind. We support
    Note: Add/Subtract/Multiply for affine offsets used in index expressions.
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
    Let in_count be proc length from List with inputs

    If in_count is equal to 2:
        Let l_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 0
        Let r_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 1
        Let l_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with l_edge
        Let r_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with r_edge

        Let l_range be compute_value_range(graph, l_src)
        Let r_range be compute_value_range(graph, r_src)
        Let l_min be proc get from List with l_range, 0
        Let l_max be proc get from List with l_range, 1
        Let r_min be proc get from List with r_range, 0
        Let r_max be proc get from List with r_range, 1

        Note: Add (OpKind 0): [l_min+r_min, l_max+r_max]
        If op_kind is equal to 0:
            Let new_min be l_min plus r_min
            Let new_max be l_max plus r_max
            Set range to proc create from List
            proc append from List with range, new_min
            proc append from List with range, new_max
            Return range
        End If
        Note: Subtract (OpKind 1): [l_min-r_max, l_max-r_min]
        If op_kind is equal to 1:
            Let s_min be l_min minus r_max
            Let s_max be l_max minus r_min
            Set range to proc create from List
            proc append from List with range, s_min
            proc append from List with range, s_max
            Return range
        End If
        Note: Multiply (OpKind 2) of two non-negative ranges:
        Note: [l_min*r_min, l_max*r_max]. For general signs we'd need a
        Note: 4-way max/min; in the GPU-index domain operands are >= 0.
        If op_kind is equal to 2:
            If l_min is greater than or equal to 0:
                If r_min is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let m_min be l_min multiplied by r_min
                    Let m_max be l_max multiplied by r_max
                    Set range to proc create from List
                    proc append from List with range, m_min
                    proc append from List with range, m_max
                    Return range
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Conservative fallback range for unmodeled ops.
    Set range to proc create from List
    proc append from List with range, 0
    proc append from List with range, 1000000
    Return range
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Pointer Analysis
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Decomposes a Bifrost address computation into (base_pointer, index_expression). The canonical IR shape is Add(base, index) where the IR builder lowers every array access to this form. The proc handles three cases: Add (canonical), Multiply (index*stride with no explicit base - returns base=0), and non-arithmetic (address IS the base; index is none).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read op_kind and inputs.
2. Add (op 0): first input is base, second is index; return [base_src, index_src].
3. Multiply (op 2): return [0, address_node] (base=0, full address treated as index).
4. Other: return [address_node, 0] (the node itself is the base, no index).
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_base_index" that takes graph as Integer, address_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Bifrost addresses are Add(base, index) by construction (the IR
    Note: builder always lowers array accesses to this canonical form).
    Note: Recover both halves by structural inspection.
    Let result be proc create from List
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with address_node
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with address_node
    Let in_count be proc length from List with inputs

    Note: Add (OpKind 0): first input is the base pointer (often Input/Constant),
    Note: second input is the index expression.
    If op_kind is equal to 0:
        If in_count is greater than or equal to 2:
            Let base_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 0
            Let index_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 1
            Let base_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with base_edge
            Let index_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with index_edge
            proc append from List with result, base_src
            proc append from List with result, index_src
            Return result
        End If
    End If

    Note: Multiply (OpKind 2): a pure index*stride expression has no base;
    Note: signal "no base" with 0.
    If op_kind is equal to 2:
        proc append from List with result, 0
        proc append from List with result, address_node
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Non-arithmetic address node IS itself the base; index = none.
    proc append from List with result, address_node
    proc append from List with result, 0
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recovers the buffer size for a base pointer by tracing it to its origin. Three trustworthy origins: Input nodes (parameter type byte size known at kernel signature), Constant nodes (value treated as base size), and Allocate ops (OpKind 42 - read the size operand). Falls back to a conservative 1 MB upper bound when the origin is opaque; this preserves soundness because verify_buffer_bounds will conservatively under-approximate proven safety.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. base_ptr == 0: return 1MB fallback.
2. NodeType.Input (1): get_node_output_type then get_type_size_bytes.
3. NodeType.Constant (0): read payload at offset 8.
4. OpKind 42 (Allocate): walk the alloc node's first input; if it's a Constant, return its value. Otherwise fall back to the alloc's declared output type size.
5. Conservative 1MB fallback otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) for the typical case (single hop to allocation/input/constant). Only the allocate-with-dynamic-size case follows additional hops.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Conservative fallback preserves soundness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_buffer_size" that takes graph as Integer, base_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Trace the base pointer back to its allocator/Input. If we find:
    Note:   - An Allocate operation: read its size operand (first input).
    Note:   - An Input node: read its declared type size in bytes.
    Note:   - A Constant: treat its value as the buffer base size.
    Note: When the chain is opaque, fall back to a conservative 1 MB upper
    Note: bound which keeps subsequent overflow checks conservative.
    If base_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 1000000
    End If

    Let node_type be proc get_node_type from Node with base_ptr
    Note: Input node (NodeType 1): use the parameter's type size.
    If node_type is equal to 1:
        Let in_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with base_ptr
        Let in_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with in_type
        If in_size is greater than 0:
            Return in_size
        End If
    End If
    Note: Constant node (NodeType 0): payload value at offset 8.
    If node_type is equal to 0:
        Let const_val be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base_ptr, 8
        If const_val is greater than 0:
            Return const_val
        End If
    End If

    Note: Allocate operation (OpKind 42 by Bifrost convention).
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with base_ptr
    If op_kind is equal to 42:
        Let alloc_inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with base_ptr
        Let alloc_in_count be proc length from List with alloc_inputs
        If alloc_in_count is greater than 0:
            Let size_edge be proc get from List with alloc_inputs, 0
            Let size_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with size_edge
            Let size_type be proc get_node_type from Node with size_src
            If size_type is equal to 0:
                Let size_val be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with size_src, 8
                If size_val is greater than 0:
                    Return size_val
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Note: Allocate with dynamic size: read declared output type bytes.
        Let alloc_out_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with base_ptr
        Let alloc_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with alloc_out_type
        If alloc_size is greater than 0:
            Return alloc_size
        End If
    End If

    Note: Conservative fallback: 1 MB upper bound.
    Return 1000000
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursively computes the alignment guarantee at an address-computation node. Bifrost's calling convention guarantees 16-byte alignment for kernel parameter pointers; constant values yield gcd(value, 16); Add takes min(alignment(a), alignment(b)) because either operand's misalignment forces the result misaligned; Multiply takes product when both >= 1 because every factor of 2 in either side contributes a factor of 2 in alignment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Null pointer: ABI default 16.
2. NodeType.Input: 16 (ABI alignment).
3. NodeType.Constant: gcd-with-16 via cascade of (mod 16), (mod 8), (mod 4), (mod 2); zero treated as 16.
4. Binary op (Add at op 0): min(l_align, r_align).
5. Binary op (Multiply at op 2): l_align * r_align, capped at 16.
6. Fallback: 16 (ABI default).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Recursive descent over the address-computation DAG. O(depth_of_address_expression).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only. Cap at 16 prevents unbounded alignment promotion through multiplicative chains.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_alignment" that takes graph as Integer, address_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively compute the alignment guarantee through arithmetic:
    Note:   * Constant pointer: alignment is gcd(value, 16) if value > 0,
    Note:     else 16 (treating 0 as fully-aligned per ABI).
    Note:   * Input pointer: 16 bytes (the kernel ABI alignment contract).
    Note:   * Add(a, b): min(alignment(a), alignment(b)).
    Note:   * Multiply(a, b): alignment(a) * alignment(b) when both >= 1.
    Note: Default alignment is 16 (the Bifrost-target ABI minimum).
    If address_node is equal to 0:
        Return 16
    End If

    Let node_type be proc get_node_type from Node with address_node
    If node_type is equal to 1:
        Note: Input pointer: ABI-aligned to 16 bytes.
        Return 16
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 0:
        Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with address_node, 8
        If cv is equal to 0:
            Return 16
        End If
        Note: gcd-with-16 via descending power-of-2 probe.
        Let candidates_8 be cv modulo by 8
        Let candidates_16 be cv modulo by 16
        If candidates_16 is equal to 0:
            Return 16
        End If
        If candidates_8 is equal to 0:
            Return 8
        End If
        Let candidates_4 be cv modulo by 4
        If candidates_4 is equal to 0:
            Return 4
        End If
        Let candidates_2 be cv modulo by 2
        If candidates_2 is equal to 0:
            Return 2
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with address_node
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with address_node
    Let in_count be proc length from List with inputs
    If in_count is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let l_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 0
        Let r_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 1
        Let l_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with l_edge
        Let r_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with r_edge
        Let l_align be compute_alignment(graph, l_src)
        Let r_align be compute_alignment(graph, r_src)

        Note: Add: alignment is the minimum of the two
        If op_kind is equal to 0:
            If l_align is less than r_align:
                Return l_align
            End If
            Return r_align
        End If
        Note: Multiply: alignment is the product when both > 0
        If op_kind is equal to 2:
            Let prod be l_align multiplied by r_align
            If prod is greater than 16:
                Return 16
            End If
            Return prod
        End If
    End If

    Return 16
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Liveness Analysis
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes peak liveness over a topologically ordered node list. A value is born at its definition node and dies after its last consumer is visited. Tracking peak_live during a single forward pass gives the max simultaneous live values, which is exactly the register pressure bound. The remaining_uses Dict counts how many uses each value still has pending; when it hits zero the value is dead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Bail with [0] on empty node list.
2. Seed remaining_uses Dict: for each node n, remaining_uses[n] = |successors(n)|.
3. Forward sweep: for each node in order, increment current_live (the node's value is now alive), update max_live.
4. For each input edge, get source, decrement remaining_uses[source]; when it reaches 0, decrement current_live (source value died).
5. Return [max_live].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E): single forward pass, constant work per node and edge. Dict operations are O(1) amortized.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only graph analysis. Allocates remaining_uses Dict and result List.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_liveness" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Standard SSA liveness sweep: walk nodes in given (topological)
    Note: order and track active value count. Each node's value becomes
    Note: live at definition and dies after its last consumer. The peak
    Note: of active count is max_live. This is the same algorithm used
    Note: by compute_peak_memory_usage but counts values, not bytes.
    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes
    If node_count is equal to 0:
        Let result0 be proc create from List
        proc append from List with result0, 0
        Return result0
    End If

    Let remaining_uses be proc create from Dict
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let n be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let succs be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, n
        Let sc be proc length from List with succs
        proc set from Dict with remaining_uses, n, sc
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let current_live be 0
    Let max_live be 0

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let cur be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Set current_live to current_live plus 1
        If current_live is greater than max_live:
            Set max_live to current_live
        End If

        Let in_edges be proc get_node_inputs from Node with cur
        Let in_count be proc length from List with in_edges
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than in_count:
            Let e be proc get from List with in_edges, k
            Let src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with e
            Let prev be proc get from Dict with remaining_uses, src
            If prev is greater than 0:
                Let new_remaining be prev minus 1
                proc set from Dict with remaining_uses, src, new_remaining
                If new_remaining is equal to 0:
                    If current_live is greater than 0:
                        Set current_live to current_live minus 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc create from List
    proc append from List with result, max_live
    Return result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Memory Operations
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Filters a node list down to memory operations (Load=40, Store=41). Used by verify_memory_safety and verify_data_race_freedom as the precondition for any per-mem-op analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterate the node list, get_node_opkind on each, append to result if op_kind is 40 or 41.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_memory_operations" that takes nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let memory_ops be proc create from List

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

        Note: Load=40, Store=41
        If op_kind is equal to 40:
            proc append from List with memory_ops, node
        End If
        If op_kind is equal to 41:
            proc append from List with memory_ops, node
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return memory_ops
End Process

@Reasoning:
Determines whether two memory operations can conflict. Identical to the parallelism-analysis predicate of the same name: Load/Load never conflicts (read-read is always safe); otherwise we look at the address-producer (first input) of each op. Same producer => potential conflict; distinct producers => statically non-aliasing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Two Loads (OpKind 40 both): return 0 (no conflict).
2. Read first input from each op; bail with conflict (1) if either has no input.
3. get_edge_source on each address edge; compare. Identical sources -> 1 (potential conflict). Different -> 0 (statically non-aliasing).
@End Implementation

Process called "check_memory_conflict" that takes op1 as Integer, op2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let op1_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with op1
    Let op2_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with op2

    If op1_kind is equal to 40:
        If op2_kind is equal to 40:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let inputs1 be proc get_node_inputs from Node with op1
    Let inputs2 be proc get_node_inputs from Node with op2
    Let len1 be proc length from List with inputs1
    Let len2 be proc length from List with inputs2
    If len1 is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If len2 is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let addr1_edge be proc get from List with inputs1, 0
    Let addr2_edge be proc get from List with inputs2, 0
    Let addr1 be proc get_edge_source from Edge with addr1_edge
    Let addr2 be proc get_edge_source from Edge with addr2_edge

    If addr1 is equal to addr2:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests whether at least one of two memory ops is a Store. Used by verify_data_race_freedom: read-read conflicts are never races; a race requires at least one writer. Stores are OpKind 41.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read op_kind for each op; return true on first match against 41 (Store), false otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "has_write_operation" that takes op1 as Integer, op2 as Integer returns Boolean:
    Let op1_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with op1
    Let op2_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with op2

    Note: Store=41
    If op1_kind is equal to 41:
        Return true
    End If
    If op2_kind is equal to 41:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Collects synchronization-class operations from the node list. The Bifrost OpKind range 60..69 is reserved for synchronization primitives: 60=Barrier (work-group barrier), 61=AtomicAdd, 62=AtomicSub, 63=AtomicMin, 64=AtomicMax, 65=AtomicCAS (compare-and-swap), 66=MemoryFence (full fence), 67=AcquireFence, 68=ReleaseFence, 69=reserved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterate the node list; for each, read op_kind and append to result when 60 <= op_kind <= 69.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_sync_operations" that takes nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let sync_ops be proc create from List
    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let n be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with n
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 60:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 69:
                proc append from List with sync_ops, n
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return sync_ops
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of threads required to execute a data-parallel op of the given output type. Vector size, Matrix area (rows*cols), and Tensor shape product determine the iteration count. Used by compute_thread_count to find the maximum block size needed across the kernel.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Null type: return 1.
2. Read discriminant at offset 0.
3. Vector (2): size at offset 16.
4. Matrix (3): rows * cols at offsets 16 and 24.
5. Tensor (5): walk shape list at offset 16 and multiply all dimensions.
6. Other: return 1 (no parallelism).
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_data_parallel_threads" that takes output_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If output_type is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 0

    Note: Vector - thread count is vector size
    If discriminant is equal to 2:
        Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
        Return size
    End If

    Note: Matrix - thread count is rows * cols
    If discriminant is equal to 3:
        Let rows be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
        Let cols be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 24
        Return rows multiplied by cols
    End If

    Note: Tensor - thread count is product of dimensions
    If discriminant is equal to 5:
        Let shape_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
        If shape_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let dim_count be proc length from List with shape_ptr
            Let total_elements be 1

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than dim_count:
                Let dim be proc get from List with shape_ptr, i
                Set total_elements to total_elements multiplied by dim
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Return total_elements
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests whether n is a power of 2. Used by verify_alignment to gate the alignment check; non-power-of-2 sizes cannot have their alignment expressed as a bit mask. The test is general (correct for every magnitude, including 512, 1024 and beyond), not limited to an enumerated range of byte sizes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for non-positive values. For positive n, computes n bitwise_and (n - 1): clearing the lowest set bit yields zero only when n has exactly one set bit, i.e. when n is a power of two. Returns true in that case, false otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_power_of_two" that takes n as Integer returns Boolean:
    If n is less than or equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: A positive integer is a power of two iff clearing its lowest set bit
    Note: yields zero. n bitwise_and (n - 1) removes exactly that bit, so the
    Note: result is 0 only for 1, 2, 4, 8, ... and nonzero for any value with
    Note: two or more set bits, for all magnitudes.
    Let n_minus_1 be n minus 1
    Let cleared be n bitwise_and n_minus_1
    If cleared is equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process
